{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488801"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:58:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:58:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"546"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/546"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.03,0.22,0.02,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90293"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/546"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"546"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74546"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"266"},{"type":"tags","id":"1238"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5194"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30964"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90293"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man is about to undergo a colonoscopy after returning a positive test on a screening faecal occult blood test. The patient has no gastrointestinal symptoms. The photograph shows the view as the procedure is about to start (Image). The lesions are manually reducible.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Assuming that the colonoscopy is otherwise normal, which one of the following is the most appropriate initial advice to give to the patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High fibre diet","Sclerotherapy","Banding","Incision and drainage","Haemorrhoidectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe view shows two partially prolapsed internal haemorrhoids. As they are manually reducible, this classes them as Grade 3. The grading of haemorrhoids is as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGrade 1: Do not prolapse; located above the dentate line; often bleed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGrade 2: Prolapse with straining; spontaneously reduce\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGrade 3: Prolapse with straining; only manually reduce\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGrade 4: Irreducible prolapse; may be thrombosed or ulcerated\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the haemorrhoids remain asymptomatic, they should be able to be managed conservatively with a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh fibre diet\u003C/strong\u003E. Other conservative measure may include education regarding straining/lingering while passing stools, regular physical exercise, and avoiding medications and food that may cause diarrhoea or constipation. If mild symptoms develop, topical agents may be offered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf more troublesome symptoms develop, rubber band ligation should be offered as an outpatient. Banding is preferred to sclerotherapy as it has been shown to be more effective and require less treatment sessions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, sclerotherapy should be offered to patients who are on antiplatelet or anticoagulation therapy as the bleeding risk is significantly reduced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemorrhoidectomy is reserved for patients with severely symptomatic Grade 3 or 4 disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Asymptomatic haemorrhoids can be managed conservatively with a high fibre diet","Rubber band ligation is the procedure of choice for symptomatic disease"],"references":["UpToDate [Internet]. Uptodate.com. [cited 2022 Jan 27]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/home-and-office-treatment-of-symptomatic-hemorrhoids?search=haemorroid%20management\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1","Lohsiriwat V. Treatment of hemorrhoids: A coloproctologist\u2019s view. World J Gastroenterol [Internet]. 2015;21(31):9245\u201352. Available from: http://dx.doi.org/10.3748/wjg.v21.i31.9245"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74546"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"546"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19778"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19778"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/41ed9e63-6854-4c64-a01b-4da084bc2f0b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/41ed9e63-6854-4c64-a01b-4da084bc2f0b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74546"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-13T16:37:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-13T16:37:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"546"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90293"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","i